{"id": "15988", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15988", "title": "January 8", "text": "January 8\n\nBULLET::::- 307 – Jin Huaidi becomes emperor of China in succession to his father, Jin Huidi, despite a challenge from his uncle, Sima Ying.\nBULLET::::- 871 – Alfred the Great leads a West Saxon army to repel an invasion by Danelaw Vikings.\nBULLET::::- 1297 – François Grimaldi, disguised as a monk, leads his men to capture the fortress protecting the Rock of Monaco, establishing his family as the rulers of Monaco.\nBULLET::::- 1454 – The papal bull \"Romanus Pontifex\" awards the Kingdom of Portugal exclusive trade and colonization rights to all of Africa south of Cape Bojador.\nBULLET::::- 1499 – Louis XII of France marries Anne of Brittany in accordance with a law set by his predecessor, Charles VIII.\nBULLET::::- 1547 – The first Lithuanian-language book, \"Simple Words of Catechism\", is published in Königsberg.\nBULLET::::- 1735 – The premiere of George Frideric Handel's \"Ariodante\" takes place at the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden.\nBULLET::::- 1746 – Second Jacobite rising: Bonnie Prince Charlie occupies Stirling.\nBULLET::::- 1790 – George Washington delivers the first State of the Union address in New York City.\nBULLET::::- 1806 – Cape Colony becomes a British colony.\nBULLET::::- 1811 – An unsuccessful slave revolt is led by Charles Deslondes in St. Charles and St. James, Louisiana.\nBULLET::::- 1815 – War of 1812: Battle of New Orleans: Andrew Jackson leads American forces in victory over the British.\nBULLET::::- 1828 – The Democratic Party of the United States is organized.\nBULLET::::- 1835 – The United States national debt is zero for the only time.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: Second Battle of Springfield.\nBULLET::::- 1867 – African American men are granted the right to vote in Washington, D.C.\nBULLET::::- 1877 – Crazy Horse and his warriors fight their last battle against the United States Cavalry at Wolf Mountain, Montana Territory.\nBULLET::::- 1889 – Herman Hollerith is issued US patent #395,791 for the 'Art of Applying Statistics' — his punched card calculator.\nBULLET::::- 1904 – The Blackstone Library is dedicated, marking the beginning of the Chicago Public Library system.\nBULLET::::- 1912 – The African National Congress is founded, under the name South African Native National Congress (SANNC).\nBULLET::::- 1918 – U.S. President Woodrow Wilson announces his \"Fourteen Points\" for the aftermath of World War I.\nBULLET::::- 1920 – The steel strike of 1919 ends in a complete failure for the Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers labor union.\nBULLET::::- 1926 – Crown Prince Nguyễn Phúc Vĩnh Thuỵ ascends the throne to become the last monarch of Vietnam.\nBULLET::::- 1926 – Abdul-Aziz ibn Saud is crowned King of Hejaz.\nBULLET::::- 1936 – Kashf-e hijab decree is enforced by Reza Shah ordering the police to physically remove the Hijab from any woman in public.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – World War II: Britain introduces food rationing.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: Philippine Commonwealth troops under the Philippine Commonwealth Army units enter the province of Ilocos Sur in Northern Luzon and attack Japanese Imperial forces.\nBULLET::::- 1956 – Operation Auca: Five U.S. missionaries are killed by the Huaorani of Ecuador shortly after making contact with them.\nBULLET::::- 1961 – In France a referendum supports Charles de Gaulle's policies in Algeria.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Leonardo da Vinci's \"Mona Lisa\" is exhibited in the United States for the first time, at the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – President Lyndon B. Johnson declares a \"War on Poverty\" in the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Bowing to international pressure, President of Pakistan Zulfikar Ali Bhutto releases Bengali leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman from prison, who had been arrested after declaring the independence of Bangladesh.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – Soviet space mission \"Luna 21\" is launched.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – Watergate scandal: The trial of seven men accused of illegal entry into Democratic Party headquarters at Watergate begins.\nBULLET::::- 1975 – Ella T. Grasso becomes Governor of Connecticut, the first woman to serve as a Governor in the United States other than by succeeding her husband.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – Three bombs explode in Moscow, Russia, Soviet Union, within 37 minutes, killing seven. The bombings are attributed to an Armenian separatist group.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – \"Password Plus\" debuts on NBC.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – A local farmer reports a UFO sighting in Trans-en-Provence, France, claimed to be \"perhaps the most completely and carefully documented sighting of all time\".\nBULLET::::- 1982 – Breakup of the Bell System: AT&T agrees to divest itself of twenty-two subdivisions.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – Kegworth air disaster: British Midland Flight 92, a Boeing 737-400, crashes into the M1 motorway, killing 47 of the 126 people on board.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – Russian cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov on \"Soyuz TM-18\" leaves for Mir. He would stay on the space station until March 22, 1995, for a record 437 days in space.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – An Antonov An-32 cargo aircraft crashes into a crowded market in Kinshasa, Zaire, killing up to 223 on the ground; two of six crew members are also killed.\nBULLET::::- 2002 – President George W. Bush signs into law the No Child Left Behind Act.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – Turkish Airlines Flight 634 crashes near Diyarbakır Airport, Turkey, killing the entire crew and 70 of the 75 passengers.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – Air Midwest Flight 5481 crashes at Charlotte-Douglas Airport, Charlotte, North Carolina, killing all 21 people on board.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The , then the largest ocean liner ever built, is christened by her namesake's granddaughter, Queen Elizabeth II.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – The nuclear sub collides at full speed with an undersea mountain south of Guam. One man is killed, but the sub surfaces and is repaired.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – A 6.1-magnitude earthquake in northern Costa Rica kills 15 people and injures 32.\nBULLET::::- 2010 – Gunmen from an offshoot the Front for the Liberation of the Enclave of Cabinda attack a bus carrying the Togo national football team on its way to the 2010 Africa Cup of Nations, killing three.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – The attempted assassination of Arizona Representative Gabrielle Giffords and subsequent shooting in Casas Adobes, Arizona, in which five people were shot dead.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Joaquín Guzmán, widely regarded as the world's most powerful drug trafficker, is recaptured following his escape from a maximum security prison in Mexico.\n\nBULLET::::- 1037 – Su Dongpo, Chinese calligrapher and poet (d. 1101)\nBULLET::::- 1345 – Kadi Burhan al-Din, poet, kadi, and ruler of Sivas (d. 1398)\nBULLET::::- 1360 – Ulrich von Jungingen, German Grand Master of the Teutonic Knights (d. 1410)\nBULLET::::- 1462 – Walraven II van Brederode, Dutch nobleman (d. 1531)\nBULLET::::- 1529 – John Frederick II, duke of Saxony (d. 1595)\nBULLET::::- 1556 – Uesugi Kagekatsu, Japanese daimyō (d. 1623)\nBULLET::::- 1583 – Simon Episcopius, Dutch theologian and academic (d. 1643)\nBULLET::::- 1587 – Johannes Fabricius, German astronomer and academic (d. 1616)\nBULLET::::- 1587 – Jan Pieterszoon Coen, Governor-General of the Dutch East Indies (d. 1629)\nBULLET::::- 1589 – Ivan Gundulić, Croatian poet and playwright (d. 1638)\nBULLET::::- 1601 – Baltasar Gracián, Spanish priest and author (d. 1658)\nBULLET::::- 1628 – François-Henri de Montmorency, duc de Luxembourg, French general (d. 1695)\nBULLET::::- 1632 – Samuel von Pufendorf, German economist and jurist (d. 1694)\nBULLET::::- 1635 – Luis Manuel Fernández de Portocarrero, Spanish cardinal (d. 1709)\nBULLET::::- 1638 – Elisabetta Sirani, Italian painter (d. 1665)\nBULLET::::- 1680 – Sebastiano Conca, Italian painter (d. 1764)\nBULLET::::- 1735 – John Carroll, American archbishop, founder of Georg